"Paradigms in botany (broadly encompassing research across traditional kingdoms: animals via ecological interactions, plants/Plantae, fungi, Protista/algae via phycology, and prokaryotes Eubacteria/Monera and Archaebacteria via microbiology and microbiomes) refer to the dominant theoretical frameworks, conceptual models, methodological approaches, and shifting worldviews that guide research. These evolve through technological advances (e.g., genomics, imaging), empirical discoveries, and societal needs like climate resilience and sustainability.
biorxiv.org

1. Taxonomic and Phylogenetic Paradigms (Kingdoms/Domains Framework)
Historical Two-Kingdom to Five/Six-Kingdom Systems: Early botany treated "plants" as the vegetable kingdom (sessile, photosynthetic or fungal-like organisms). Whittaker's five-kingdom system (Monera, Protista, Fungi, Plantae, Animalia) and six-kingdom variants (splitting Monera into Eubacteria and Archaebacteria) formalized distinctions based on cell structure, nutrition, and organization.
en.wikipedia.org
Three-Domain System (Carl Woese et al.): The dominant modern paradigm, separating life into Bacteria, Archaea, and Eukarya based on rRNA and molecular phylogenetics. This shifted focus from morphology to evolutionary relationships, with endosymbiosis explaining organelles (e.g., chloroplasts from cyanobacteria). Protista remains paraphyletic; many algae link to Plantae or other eukaryotic lineages.
en.wikipedia.org +1
Cladistics and Phylogenomics: Emphasis on monophyletic groups and whole-genome data. This refines Plantae (Viridiplantae, including green algae) and reveals fungal-animal sister relationships within Opisthokonta.
ebsco.com

2. Reductionist to Systems/Holistic Paradigms
Molecular/Genomic Era: Post-Arabidopsis genome, focus on genes, pathways, and model organisms (e.g., Arabidopsis thaliana for plants, Saccharomyces for fungi). This enabled CRISPR editing and synthetic biology but faced critiques for overlooking complexity.
biorxiv.org
Systems Biology and Networks: Shift to integrative models of signaling, metabolism, and gene regulatory networks. Functional-structural plant models (FSPM) combine physiology with morphology for predictive simulation.
academic.oup.com
Plant Neurobiology (controversial but influential): Proposes plants sense, communicate, and adapt via electrical/chemical signals, challenging animal-centric views of intelligence/behavior.
pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov

3. Holobiont and Microbiome Paradigm (Cross-Kingdom Integration)
This is a major contemporary paradigm shift: organisms are not isolated but holobionts—the host plus its symbiotic microbiome (bacteria, archaea, fungi, protists).
pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov +1

Plants actively shape their rhizosphere/phyllosphere microbiomes for nutrient uptake, stress resistance, and immunity.
Extends to fungi (mycorrhizae), algae (symbioses), and prokaryotes (e.g., nitrogen-fixers, PGPR—plant growth-promoting rhizobacteria).
Implications for ecology, evolution (co-evolution), and applications (microbiome engineering for sustainable agriculture).
cell.com
Animal interactions fit via pollinators, herbivores, and ecosystem networks.

4. Evolutionary and Ecological Paradigms
Modern Synthesis and Evo-Devo: Integrates Darwinian selection with genetics, applied to plant speciation, alternation of generations, and transitions (e.g., algae to land plants).
ebsco.com
Community and Ecosystem Ecology: Plants/fungi/protists as primary producers or decomposers in food webs; emphasis on biodiversity, succession, and resilience. Climate change drives research on carbon sequestration and invasives.
Symbiosis Paradigms: Mutualism, commensalism, pathogenesis across kingdoms (e.g., fungal endophytes, bacterial/archaeal roles in nutrient cycling).
frontiersin.org

5. Applied and Translational Paradigms
Crop Improvement and Sustainability: From classical breeding to genomics-enabled precision agriculture, with focus on resilience (drought, pathogens) and biofortification.
Biotechnology and Bioeconomy: Algal biofuels, fungal metabolites, bacterial engineering, and myco-materials.
Data-Driven/AI Paradigms: Topic modeling, machine learning for phenotyping, phylogenomics, and predictive ecology. Shifts from hypothesis-driven to big-data exploratory approaches.
biorxiv.org

Shifts and Country/Topic Dynamics
Analyses of plant science literature show transitions from pre-molecular (taxonomy, physiology) to molecular/genomic dominance, with recent radiations in stress biology, microbiomes, and development. Model organisms vary by region and era; interdisciplinary work (e.g., with ecology or AI) is rising.
biorxiv.org

Challenges and Emerging Views: Critiques of over-reductionism call for more "T-shaped" researchers (deep + broad knowledge) and better integration of field realities with lab models. Taxonomy and classical botany retain importance amid biodiversity crises, while multi-kingdom holobiont studies bridge gaps.
